Q: What do you notice about the pattern of missing data?

A: The first thing to notice is that all the features(columns) in the graph overlap,
indicating that all sensors' measurements were missing at the same datetimes which might be due to a blackout.
If the connectivity was down, and the sensors would had technical issues simultaneously.
Also, in 2008 and 2009, there were almost no missing data.
Q: What method makes the most sense to you for dealing with our missing data and why? (There isn't necessarily a single right answer here)

A:The bar plot shows that the missing data is around 25000, and the total count of 2049280,
which makes it safe to drop the 1% missing data.

Q: What patterns do you see in the monthly data? Do any of the variables seem to move together?

A: The monthly average is a much cleaner data visualization, which helps get insights. A noticeable dip in
all variables simultaneously in mid-2008 may be because there was a power outage causing the simultaneous
dip. There is a simultaneous decrease in the Global_intensity and the Sub_metering_3 around the middle of
each year. One interpretation could be that the weather conditions get better around spring or early
summer (April through June) hence the need for less water heating or AC usage.
The Global_intensity and Sub_metering_3 move together with almost the same dips and humps.

Data Covariance and Correlation

Let's take a look at the Correlation Matrix for the four global power variables in the dataset.

In [79]:
axes = pd.plotting.scatter_matrix(df[['Global_active_power', 'Global_reactive_power', 'Voltage', 'Global_intensity']], alpha=0.5,figsize = [10,10])
corr = df[['Global_active_power', 'Global_reactive_power', 'Voltage', 'Global_intensity']].corr(method = 'spearman').to_numpy() #nonlinear
for i, j in zip(*plt.np.triu_indices_from(axes, k=1)):
    axes[i, j].annotate("%.3f" %corr[i,j], (0.8, 0.8), xycoords='axes fraction', ha='center', va='center')
plt.show()

Q: Describe any patterns and correlations that you see in the data. What effect does this have on how we use this data in downstream tasks?

A: The correlation covariance scatterplots and the Spearman rho correlation matrices show that the
Global_active_power and the Global_intensity are highly correlated. Having a Spearman matrix of 0.995, almost 1.
At the same time, we can not see any meaningful correlation between other global power variables.
The high correlation between the Global_intensity and the Global_active_power makes them interchangeable
when predicting the Sub-metering values. Then Global intensity, Global reactive power, and Voltage
would be the possible independent variables used in the ML prediction models for the Sub-metering values
of the household appliances.
